<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">This vocabulary was developed as part of the EU-funded project DE-BIAS - Detecting and cur(at)ing harmful language in cultural heritage collections (2023/2024). The project aimed to promote a more inclusive and respectful approach to describing digital collections by developing an AI-based tool to identify and contextualise the outdated or potentially harmful terms in this vocabulary in object descriptions from cultural heritage institutions. For more information about the project and further documentation, please visit Europeana Pro: https://pro.europeana.eu/project/de-bias

Content note: Readers are advised that this document contains distressing words

The terms in the vocabulary cover the languages English, Dutch, German, French, and Italian and are accompanied by contextual information and, where appropriate, suggestions for reflection and alternative wording. These recommendations guide users in dealing with controversial language in metadata and aim to raise awareness of current linguistic sensitivities. This vocabulary focuses primarily on migration and colonial history, gender and sexual identity, and ethnicity and ethno-religious identity, with some terms relating to other minority communities. Developed with input from under-represented groups and research into over 100 existing glossaries and (academic) publications, it cites these sources for the description of each term. This vocabulary captures the discussions surrounding these terms at the time of publication. It is intended to be a living document and will continue to be updated beyond the end of the project as the discourse evolves.
The Knowledge Graph model developed for this vocabulary is based on the Words Matter Knowledge Graph by Cultural AI (1) and this paper (2) with additions and adjustments for the DE-BIAS tool needs and SKOS compatibility. One deviation from the SKOS schema is the absence of a skos:prefLabel on the skos:Concept. Instead, dcterms:title was chosen to apply a nominator to the concepts grouping the contentious terms.

(1) Andrei Nesterov, Laura Hollink, Marieke van Erp, and Jacco van Ossenbruggen. (2023). cultural-ai/wordsmatter: Words Matter: a knowledge graph of contentious terms (v1.0.2) [Data set]. European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC), Hersonissos, Greece. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7713157
(2) Nesterov, A., Hollink, L., van Erp, M., van Ossenbruggen, J. (2023). A Knowledge Graph of Contentious Terminology for Inclusive Representation of Cultural Heritage. In: Pesquita, C., et al. The Semantic Web. ESWC 2023. Lecture Notes in Computer Science, vol 13870. Springer, Cham. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-33455-9_30</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2025-09-29</modified>
