<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_164_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_11"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_7"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_100_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">The term “hag” is used to describe an older woman, usually in a negative way, suggesting she is unattractive, unpleasant, or mean. This characterization is rooted in misogynistic and ageist stereotypes that degrade and diminish women as they age.</description>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Cultural Heritage Terminology Network, “Inclusive Terminology Glossary. 3.2 Women's History,” 2024, accessed April 3, 2024, https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tpZmKNmmNAttiXKGKgV2u3suvPgZbTrsiMnNRW9MHsc/edit.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Hag</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_104_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_9"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_149_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Terms for mixed race people, many of which are perceived as derogatory through implication that these people are less than 'whole'. In the UK, the terms 'mixed race' and 'multiracial' tend to be used interchangeably, but are criticised for being homogenising.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-12-03</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Cultural Heritage Terminology Network, “Inclusive Terminology Glossary. 1.6 Empires and Imperialism,” 2024, accessed April 3, 2024, https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qCKze8kPN69b12mejnUk7_ZJ2ny14le0E-jnpo-94QY/edit.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Mixed</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<deprecated xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean">true</deprecated>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_110_nl">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_6"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_9"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_2"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_3"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_120_nl"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="nl">Met ‘politionele acties’ worden de grootschalige militaire operaties van het Nederlandse leger tussen 1945-1949 bedoeld, die erop gericht waren om Indonesische Onafhankelijkheid te voorkomen. De Nederlandse regering wilde oorlogsterminologie vermijden, omdat zij de operaties zagen als een legitieme onderdrukking van een opstand. Zij gebruikten de term ‘politionele actie’. ‘Politionele actie’ wordt om die reden als een misleidend begrip gezien, onder meer door de nazaten van slachtoffers. Het wordt beschouwd als een eufemistische term, die de structurele inmenging van het leger en de gewelddadigheden verdoezelt en de slachtoffers reduceert tot rebellen.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2025-01-30</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Tropen Museum et al., eds., “Woorden doen ertoe: Een Incomplete Gids voor woordkeuze binnen de culturele sector,” 2018, 136. https://www.materialculture.nl/sites/default/files/2018-09/WordsMatter_DEF_Totale_PDF_NL.pdf.</source>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Andrei Nesterov, Laura Hollink, Marieke van Erp, and Jacco van Ossenbruggen. (2023). cultural-ai/wordsmatter: Words Matter: a knowledge graph of contentious terms (v1.0.2) [Data set]. European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC), Hersonissos, Greece. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7713157 ; https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/136_nl.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="nl">Politionele actie</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0005"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0005"/>
	<exactMatch xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/136_nl"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_4_fr">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_6"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_2"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_4_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_5_fr"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Ce terme est injurieux et péjoratif quand on parle d'une personne. Chez les Français d’outre-mer descendants de la traite de Noirs, en particulier aux Antilles françaises, insulte désignant les Français originaire d’outre-mer à qui on reproche de ne pas se distancier des Français métropolitains.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-11-25</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“assimilé,” in Wiktionnaire Le Dictionnaire Libre, n.d., accessed April 3, 2024, https://fr.wiktionary.org/wiki/assimil%C3%A9.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Assimilé / Assimilée</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_23_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_2"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_27_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">The term “brute” refers to a large animal or a person who behaves in a cruel or vulgar manner. While it's generally acceptable when referring to animals or even white people, it has a history of being used by Europeans as a dehumanising label for non-white populations, which makes its use in this context offensive.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-12-02</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Cultural Heritage Terminology Network, “Inclusive Terminology Glossary. 1.6 Empires and Imperialism,” 2024, accessed April 3, 2024, https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qCKze8kPN69b12mejnUk7_ZJ2ny14le0E-jnpo-94QY/edit.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Brute</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_6_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_9"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_8"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_6_en"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_231_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">People of African descent have widely varied cultural backgrounds, family histories, and family experiences. Some American people of African ancestry prefer “Black,” and others prefer “African American”; both terms are acceptable. However, “African American” should not be used as an umbrella term for people of African ancestry worldwide because it obscures other ethnicities or national origins, such as Nigerian, Kenyan, Jamaican, or Bahamian. The terms “Negro” and “Afro-American” are outdated.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-12-02</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“Racial and Ethnic Identity,” apastyle.apa.org, n.d., accessed April 3, 2024, https://apastyle.apa.org/style-grammar-guidelines/bias-free-language/racial-ethnic-minorities.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Afro-American / African American</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_13_fr">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_5"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_21_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_20_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_85_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_86_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_84_fr"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_83_fr"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Il est recommandé d'utiliser ce mot comme adjectif et de placer le mot « personne » devant afin de ne pas confondre la personne avec le handicap auquel elle est confrontée.</description>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Association Le Phenix, “Choisir le mot juste pour parler de handicaps ,” n.d., https://campsquebec.com/upload/tools/outils-integration-reussie/Choisir_le_mot_juste.pdf.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Un handicapé / Une handicapée</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_7_fr"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_9_fr"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_14_fr"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_6_fr"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_30_it">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_11"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_39_it"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="it">L'aggettivo riguarda l'amore o l'attrazione sessuale tra due donne. Deriva dal latino Sapphĭcus, greco Sapphikós, e deriva dal nome di Saffo, la famosa poetessa greca</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-12-20</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“Saffico,” in Treccani, n.d., accessed April 2, 2024, https://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/saffico_(Sinonimi-e-Contrari)/.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="it">Saffico</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
