<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_76_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_7"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_109_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">The word comes from Latin and Greek, named after Hermaphroditus, the child of Hermes and Aphrodite, who in mythology had both male and female traits. It entered English in the late 14th century. From the Victorian era to the 21st century, medical experts used strict definitions: “true hermaphrodites” had both ovarian and testicular tissue, while “pseudohermaphrodites” had mismatched external and internal traits. These terms are now regarded as outdated and stigmatizing.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2024-12-04</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“Hermaphrodite,” Wikipedia, December 2, 2024, accessed November 21, 2024, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermaphrodite.</source>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Tropen Museum et al., eds., “Words Matter: An Unfinished Guide to Word Choices in the Cultural Sector,” 2018, 112. https://www.materialculture.nl/sites/default/files/2018-08/words_matter.pdf.pdf.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Hermaphrodite</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<exactMatch xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_54_de"/>
	<exactMatch xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_53_nl"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_53_en"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_19_en"/>
	<hasSuggestedTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/a_52_en"/>
	<closeMatch xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/112"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_53_nl">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_7"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_54_nl"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="nl">‘Hermafrodiet’ wordt gezien als een ouderwetse en stigmatiserende term, die mensen pathologiseert die geboren zijn met de geslachtsorganen van beide geslachten.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2025-01-30</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Tropen Museum et al., eds., “Woorden doen ertoe: Een Incomplete Gids voor woordkeuze binnen de culturele sector,” 2018, 112. https://www.materialculture.nl/sites/default/files/2018-09/WordsMatter_DEF_Totale_PDF_NL.pdf.</source>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Andrei Nesterov, Laura Hollink, Marieke van Erp, and Jacco van Ossenbruggen. (2023). cultural-ai/wordsmatter: Words Matter: a knowledge graph of contentious terms (v1.0.2) [Data set]. European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC), Hersonissos, Greece. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7713157 ; https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/112_nl.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="nl">Hermafrodiet</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0005"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0005"/>
	<exactMatch xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/112_nl"/>
