<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_85_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_5"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_3"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_120_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">In its early English sense referred to people considered unable to look after themselves for reasons of age, infirmity, or disability. The 'impotent poor' were distinguished from the 'able bodied' poor in legislation.</description>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Cultural Heritage Terminology Network, “Inclusive Terminology Glossary. 5. Working Class History,” 2024, accessed April 3, 2024, https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dz6XNaJbO1v85OAlCeyL6HXO27__S7e3jOnC8YG-8Zo/edit.</source>
