	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_31_fr">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_49_fr"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Néologisme péjoratif désignant une proximité supposée entre des idéologies, personnalités ou partis de gauche et les milieux musulmans, voire islamistes.</description>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“Islamo-gauchisme,” in Wikipédia, l'encyclopédie libre, n.d., accessed April 3, 2024, https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamo-gauchisme.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="fr">Islamo-gauchiste</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0006"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_171_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_9"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_182_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">An outdated term that white people used in the 19th and throughout the early 20th century to refer to people who had one grandparent that was perceived as Black or African American and the rest of their parentage was white (in cruder terms, someone who was “one-quarter” Black).</description>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">“CHM Research Guides - LibGuides at Chicago History Museum,” August 20, 2021, accessed December 2, 2024. https://libguides.chicagohistory.org/blog/African-American-and-Black-Identity-and-Research-Terms.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Quadroon</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
	<topConceptOf xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0002"/>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/c_152_en">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept"/>
	<hasBiasCategory xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/cat_9"/>
	<hasContentiousTerm xmlns="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/ontology#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/t_218_en"/>
	<description xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">This term has long been used to describe a racial identity, based on skin colour, and usually describes certain groups of Europeans and their emigrant population across the world. The term is associated with the racial sciences of the 18th and 19th centuries. Since the latter part of the 20th century there has been sustained critique of the social construction of Whiteness as norm, arguing that it is an identity category that emerged to justify or reinforce discrimination against non-White people.</description>
	<modified xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2025-01-31</modified>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Tropen Museum et al., eds., “Words Matter: An Unfinished Guide to Word Choices in the Cultural Sector,” 2018, 144. https://www.materialculture.nl/sites/default/files/2018-08/words_matter.pdf.pdf.</source>
	<source xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">Andrei Nesterov, Laura Hollink, Marieke van Erp, and Jacco van Ossenbruggen. (2023). cultural-ai/wordsmatter: Words Matter: a knowledge graph of contentious terms (v1.0.2) [Data set]. European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC), Hersonissos, Greece. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7713157 ; https://w3id.org/culco/wordsmatter/144.</source>
	<title xmlns="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xml:lang="en">White</title>
	<inScheme xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#" rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/c4p/data/0001"/>
